author: @ozgurcoban7074
text: Just as @sentdex mentioned, there actually is a better way to handle the colors.   If you take a peek at /materialize-src/sass/components you'll find a .scss file called _navbar.scss. When lurking around here I noticed that it refers to something called $primary-color. Now that means that somewhere within the sass folder we're setting a primary color. I lurked around a bit more... and found that we do exactly that in the _variables.scss file. If you proceed to open this file you'll find that it is setting $primary-color to materialize-red.   All you need to do now is change that to whatever color you want, so there's no need to mess with the color configurations! Compile using Koala and you're good to go.

author: @17Codiferus
text: Some useful django stuff that most beginner tutorials completely miss: Custom context processors. Using jinja2 tags/flow control in javascript (everyone only shows html). You CAN use multiple {% block my_block %}{% endblock %} defs (with unique names) to control where content gets loaded into the DOM (usefult for dynamic headers, page titles/descriptions, and loading js as needed). Management scripts, add management options to your app/data using the manage.py CLI.  Modifying migrations to set up your app-database with some default data/settings (maybe you always want the same pre-configured auth groups/permissions).  These are some of the things I could or would have used on my first few django projects, but didn't figure out until later.
